## Usage

The default variant includes `gcc`, `g++`, `make`, and the GNU C Library development headers. The `-builder` variants additionally include `gdb`.

### Using a Multi-stage Build

For production-ready images, use a multi-stage build. Compile in the C image and copy the resulting binary to a minimal runtime image.

```dockerfile
# Build stage
FROM {{ readme_targets[target].registry }}/c:latest AS builder
WORKDIR /app
COPY . .
RUN make

# Runtime stage
FROM {{ readme_targets[target].registry }}/core-runtime:latest
COPY --from=builder /app/myapp /usr/bin/myapp
ENTRYPOINT ["/usr/bin/myapp"]
```

### Using Builder Variants

The `-builder` variants include the `dnf` package manager and additional tools such as `gdb`. Use these variants if the application requires additional packages or debugging tools during the build stage.

```dockerfile
# Build stage
FROM {{ readme_targets[target].registry }}/c:latest-builder AS builder
RUN dnf install -y <packages> && dnf clean all
WORKDIR /app
COPY . .
RUN make

# Runtime stage
FROM {{ readme_targets[target].registry }}/core-runtime:latest
COPY --from=builder /app/myapp /usr/bin/myapp
ENTRYPOINT ["/usr/bin/myapp"]
```

